Hello!

* Type: new feature
* Link to issue:https://github.com/phalcon/cphalcon/issues/13378

**In raising this pull request, I confirm the following:**

- [x] I have read and understood the [Contributing Guidelines](https://github.com/phalcon/cphalcon/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md)
- [x] I have checked that another pull request for this purpose does not exist
- [x] I wrote some tests for this PR
- [ ] I have updated the relevant CHANGELOG
- [ ] I have created a PR for the [documentation](https://github.com/phalcon/docs) about this change

Small description of change: This is basic concept of autowire component for Phalcon's Di. How it works:

When creating `Phalcon\Di` there is optional argument implementing interface `Phalcon\Di\AutowireInterface`:

```php
$di = new \Phalcon\Di(new \Phalcon\Di\Autowire());
```

Which is used by `Phalcon\Di->get()` when called with string(class name) like this:

```php
$di->get(\Test\TestService::class); // or:
$di->set('testService', \Test\TestService::class);
$di->get('testService');
```

It analyzes constructor arguments and if they are classes tries to automatically get them from container and then creates new instance.

It also adds way to bind classes or interfaces, it will allow to either bind implementations to interfaces or add autowiring using currently written services to new projects. It also supports multiple implementations for one interfaces, to use then different implementation for different service developer needs to tell which exactly implementation he wants to use.

**Case with interface:**

Classes:

```php
namespace Test;

interface TestInterface
{
    public function test();
}

class TestService
{
    protected $testClass;

    public function __construct(TestInterface $test, $xyz)
    {
        $this->testClass = $test;
    }
}

class TestClass implements TestInterface
{
    protected $test;

    public function __construct()
    {
        $this->test = rand();
    }

    public function test()
    {
        // TODO: Implement test() method.
    }
}
```

Code:

```php
$di->bind(\Test\TestInterface::class, \Test\TestClass::class, true); // 3rd argument is to tell that this should be resolved as shared, so it will always return the same instance
var_dump($di->get(\Test\TestService::class));
var_dump($di->get(\Test\TestService::class));
```

Output:

```
object(Test\TestService)#10 (1) {
  ["testClass":protected]=>
  object(Test\TestClass)#8 (1) {
    ["test":protected]=>
    int(601129658)
  }
}
object(Test\TestService)#10 (1) {
  ["testClass":protected]=>
  object(Test\TestClass)#8 (1) {
    ["test":protected]=>
    int(601129658)
  }
}
```

When class we try to resolve has some other parameters like:

```
class TestService
{
    protected $testClass;

    public function __construct(TestInterface $test, $xyz)
    {
        $this->testClass = $test;
    }
}
```

This service then can be resolved like this:

```php
$di->get(\Test\TestService::class, ['xyz' => '123'])
```

Default parameters will be used if they exists, can be overridden the same way via second argument of get.

**Case with existing service**(you can also bind existing service to class name, and use then class name in __construct, it will automatically resolve to your existing service):

Code:

```php
$di->set('xyz', function () {
    return new \Test\TestClass();
}, true);
$di->bind(\Test\TestInterface::class, 'xyz', true);
var_dump($di->get(\Test\TestService::class));
var_dump($di->get(\Test\TestService::class));
```

Output:

```
 object(Test\TestService)#10 (1) {
  ["testClass":protected]=>
  object(Test\TestClass)#8 (1) {
    ["test":protected]=>
    int(601129658)
  }
}
object(Test\TestService)#10 (1) {
  ["testClass":protected]=>
  object(Test\TestClass)#8 (1) {
    ["test":protected]=>
    int(601129658)
  }
}
```

**Case with multiple implementations:**

Additional implementation:

```php
class TestClassOther implements TestInterface
{
    public function test()
    {
        // TODO: Implement test() method.
    }
}
```

Code:

```php
$di->bind(\Test\TestInterface::class, \Test\TestClass::class, true);
$di->bind(\Test\TestInterface::class, \Test\TestClassOther::class, true);
$di->set('testService', \Test\TestService::class)
    ->setAutowireTypes([\Test\TestInterface::class => \Test\TestClass::class]);
$di->set('testServiceOther', \Test\TestService::class)
    ->setAutowireTypes([\Test\TestInterface::class => \Test\TestClassOther::class]);
var_dump($di->get('testService'));
var_dump($di->get('testServiceOther'));
```

Output:

```
object(Test\TestService)#15 (1) {
  ["testClass":protected]=>
  object(Test\TestClass)#13 (1) {
    ["test":protected]=>
    int(1528930295)
  }
}
object(Test\TestService)#12 (1) {
  ["testClass":protected]=>
  object(Test\TestClassOther)#15 (0) {
  }
}
```

Things to consider(let me know what you think about these):

- automatically resolve multiple implementations of interface based on parameter name and/or resolved class name, not sure if it would be anyhow usefull and also it would add some bottleneck, need to figure out how it should work
- add interface `Phalcon\Di\AutowireAwareInterface` so only classes implementing it will be auto wired(though empty interface doing nothing feels kind of weird)
- add way to set non-class parameters for nested services - currently when resolving you can set non-class parameters only for resolving class, for nested classes it would need more work, either set them using bind, or add method to ServiceInterface to set constructor parameters for example
- component itself adds option to set Autowire to resolve not defined classes via set/bind as shared - not sure if this should be kept or not
- ~caching - needs tests how exactly it affects performance~ - not worth it, performance hit is really low, and any caching is not required, just localCache storing in property already resolved parameters for methods
- `Phalcon\Di::set` method is also changed, when definition is a class it will automatically bind it so it will be ready for autowire - it's just way to make it work if someone already uses calls like `$di->set('xyz', Class::class)`, it's to avoid unnecessary bind calls by developer
- add some kind of method like updateBinds to container - which will fetch all defined services, check if their definition is class/object not being closure and will add them to bind so autowire will resolve it with ease(we might also store it in some cache)
- since bind calls are pretty much pair of strings and bool add way to also implement cache for it to avoid method calls - what im thinking is it could be good for example add new method to `ServiceProviderInterface` in 5.0, for now create interface like maybe `ServiceProviderProvisionInterface` or `ServiceProviderCacheInterface` - which will be called only if container cache was empty
- ~resolve onConstruct methods called in a framework~ - **DONE**
- ~when using bind method with class as first argument(not interface) fetch also interfaces which class implements and add them as well(so either we will use interface or class in `__construct` it will get resolved)~ - implemented as option to enable, disabled by default
- is BindDefinition class necessary - we could just operate only on arrays and reduce memory usage
- add method resolver for autowire and implement it in dispatcher - so when user typehint class in action it will get resolved(separated feature request if this will get implemented and added?) - method resolver is done pretty much

Thanks

