        return [
            'device_id'                 => 'id',
            'device_serial'             => 'serial',
            'device_name'               => 'name'
        ];
    }

    public function initialize()
    {
        $this->setSource('device');
        $this->setSchema('hardware');

        $this->hasMany('id', DeviceToSite::class, 'device_id');
        $this->hasManyToMany('id', DeviceToSite::class, 'device_id', 'site_id', Site::class, 'id');
    }
}
```
```php
namespace App\Model\Device;

use App\Model\Device\Device;
use App\Model\Site\Site;

class DeviceToSite extends \Phalcon\Mvc\Model
{
    public function columnMap()
    {
        return [
            'device_id'         => 'device_id',
            'site_id'           => 'site_id'
        ];
    }

    public function initialize()
    {
        $this->setSource('device_to_site');
        $this->setSchema('app');

        $this->belongsTo('device_id', Device::class, 'id');
        $this->belongsTo('site_id', Site::class, 'id');
    }
}
```

```php
namespace App\Model\Site;

class Site extends \Phalcon\Mvc\Model
{
    public function columnMap()
    {
        return [
            'site_id'           => 'id',
            'site_name'         => 'name'
        ];
    }

    public function initialize()
    {
        $this->setSource('site');
        $this->setSchema('app');
    }
}
```

My MySQL connector points to the **hardware** schema by default
```php
use Phalcon\Db\Adapter\Pdo\Mysql;

$config = [
    "host"     => "localhost",
    "dbname"   => "hardware",
    "port"     => 3306,
    "username" => "demo",
    "password" => "demo",
];

$connection = new Mysql($config);
```

A sample query would then look like this to get all the devices belonging to the site with ID 1

```php
use App\Model\Device\Device;
use App\Model\Device\DeviceToSite;
use App\Model\Site\Site;

$devices = $this
    ->modelsManager
    ->createBuilder()
    ->from(Device::class)
    ->join(Site::class, '[' . Site::class . '].id = 1')
    ->getQuery()
    ->execute();    
```

Everything is working fine when the tables are in the same schema. Only when the tables are spread across multiple schemas, the query doesn't fully reference the intermediate model's schema, but rather uses the default schema as setup in the config

This PR seems to fix the issue in my application 

Please let me know should you require more code or examples

